n="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">History of multiple fractures</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">+</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#8722;</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#8722;</td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Blood cell count</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Thrombocytopenia</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Normal</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Normal</td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Renal findings</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#8722;</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Unilateral kidney atrophy</td><td align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#8722;</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><p>This additional case of biallelic <italic toggle="yes">PDCD6IP</italic> variants further supports its role in a novel neurodevelopmental disorder with microcephaly. All three known cases involve consanguineous families, indicating these variants are likely extremely rare in the general population. As <italic toggle="yes">PDCD6IP</italic> is not yet classified as a disease&#8208;causing gene, its pathogenic variants may be underrecognized. Our case highlights the importance of including <italic toggle="yes">PDCD6IP</italic> as a disease&#8208;causing gene in patients with intellectual disability and microcephaly.</p><sec sec-type="COI-statement" id="cge70025-sec-0003"><title>Conflicts of Interest</title><p>The authors declare no conflicts of interest.</p></sec><sec sec-type="peer-review" id="cge70025-sec-0006"><title>Peer Review</title><p>The peer review history for this article is available at <ext-link xlink:href="https://www.webofscience.com/api/gateway/wos/peer-review/10.1111/cge.70025" ext-link-type="uri">https://www.webofscience.com/api/gateway/wos/peer&#8208;review/10.1111/cge.